{{short description|British philosopher}} {{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|21st-century philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''Bob Brecher''' |birth_date = 1949 |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = | institutions = [[University of Brighton]] |main_interests = [[political philosophy]], [[ethics]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = |notable_ideas = | spouse = | education = [[University of Kent]] (BA & PhD) | alma_mater = |influences = |influenced = |awards = [[British Academy]] award |website = }}
'''Bob Brecher''' (born 1949) is a British philosopher and Professor of [[Philosophy]] at the [[University of Brighton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Bob Brecher |url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/author/bob-brecher |website=[[OpenDemocracy]] |accessdate=28 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref> He is known for his expertise on [[ethics]] and [[political philosophy]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Coady |first1=C. A. J. |title=Review of Torture and the Ticking Bomb |journal=Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews |date=28 February 2009 |url=https://ndpr.nd.edu/news/torture-and-the-ticking-bomb/ |accessdate=28 November 2018 |issn=1538-1617}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bertram |first1=CDI |title=Book Review of Getting What You Want? A Critique of Liberal Morality by Bob Brecher |url=https://research-information.bristol.ac.uk/en/publications/book-review-of-getting-what-you-want-a-critique-of-liberal-morality-by-bob-brecher(74bf451f-2201-4fe0-b799-67dabe9a8550).html |website=Philosophical books |accessdate=28 November 2018 |language=English |date=1999}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Griseri |first1=Paul |title=The Ideal of Professionalism |journal=Philosophy of Management |date=2005 |volume=5 |issue=3 |pages=71–78 |doi=10.5840/pom2005537 |url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.5840/pom2005537 |accessdate=28 November 2018 |language=en |issn=1740-3812}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Marsella |first1=Anthony J. |title=Review: Torture and the Ticking Bomb |url=http://engagingpeace.com/?p=9843 |website=engagingpeace.com |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Miller |first1=Paul J. W. |title=Anselm's Argument. The Logic of Divine Existence (review) |journal=Journal of the History of Philosophy |date=1989 |volume=27 |issue=4 |pages=612–613 |doi=10.1353/hph.1989.0096 |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/226471/summary |accessdate=28 November 2018 |language=en |issn=1538-4586}}</ref> Brecher is co-director of [[Centre for Applied Philosophy, Politics and Ethics]] and a former president of Association for Social and Political Philosophy (2000-2003). He founded ''[[Res Publica (journal)|Res Publica]]'' in 1995.
