'''Linguistic film theory'''<ref name=Dualist>''The Dualist'' [https://books.google.gr/books?id=N1u6AAAAIAAJ&dq= Vols. 1–6], Department of Philosophy, Stanford University, 1994, p. 56.</ref> is a form of [[film theory]] that studies the [[aesthetics]] of film by investigating the concepts and practices that comprise the experience and [[Aesthetic interpretation|interpretation]] of movies. 

==Overview==
Linguistic film theory was proposed by [[Stanley Cavell]]<ref name=Dualist/> and it is based on the philosophical tradition begun by [[late Ludwig Wittgenstein]]. The theory itself is said to mirror aspects of the activity of Wittgenstein's own philosophising (e.g. Wittgenstein's thought experiments) as films are viewed capable of engaging the audience in a therapeutic process of 'dialogue' and even investigate the [[Absurdity|absurd]] and the limits of thought.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Film as Philosophy: Essays in Cinema after Wittgenstein and Cavell|last=Read|first=Rupert|last2=Goodenough|first2=Jerry|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2005|isbn=9781403997951|location=New York|pages=30}}</ref> Cavell's framework is seen as a distinctive way of approaching film and [[philosophy]] since question of style - the finding of words adequate to our aesthetic experience - is central to the understanding of the meaning of films.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shaw|first=Daniel|date=2017|title=Stanley Cavell on the Magic of the Movies|url=https://www.euppublishing.com/doi/full/10.3366/film.2017.0034|journal=Film-Philosophy|language=en|volume=21|issue=1|pages=114–132|doi=10.3366/film.2017.0034|issn=1466-4615|via=}}</ref> One of his ideas involved the position that "if one thinks of a grammar as a machine for generating sentences, then perhaps one will wish to speak of the camera and its film as a machine for generating idioms."<ref>{{Cite book|title=The World Viewed: Reflections on the Ontology of Film|last=Cavell|first=Stanley|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1979|isbn=067496196X|location=Cambridge, MA|pages=204}}</ref>

Critics from this tradition often clarify misconceptions used in theoretical film studies<ref>{{cite book
 | editor1= [[David Bordwell]] |editor2=[[Noël Carroll]] | year=1996
 | title=Post-Theory: Reconstructing Film Studies 
 | edition= 
 | publisher=University of Wisconsin Press
 | location=Madison 
 | page=109
}}</ref><ref>Annette Kuhn and Guy Westwell (2012). "Post-theory" in ''A Dictionary of Film Studies''. Oxford: Oxford University Press.</ref> and instead produce analysis of a film's vocabulary and its link to a [[Form of life (philosophy)|form of life]].

