{{Moroccan literature}} '''Mohammed Aziz Lahbabi''' (born December 25, 1922, [[Fes]], died on August 23, 1993, [[Rabat]]) was a Moroccan philosopher, novelist and poet writing in Arabic and French. Some of his books were translated into more than 30 languages. Lahbabi studied at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in [[Paris]] and received a doctorate of philosophy. He was professor of philosophy and dean of the faculty of letters at the [[Mohammed V University|Mohammed V]] University in [[Rabat]]. Characteristic of his philosophical writings is the union of Arab-Islamic and Western-humanistic ideas.<ref>Ibrahim M. Abu-Rabi, ''Intellectual Origins of Islamic Resurgence in the Modern Arab World'', ed. SUNY Press, 1996, {{ISBN|978-0-7914-2663-0}}, p. 30: "Lahbabi, unquestionably one of the most important intellectual figures in contemporary North Africa"</ref><ref>[[Edward Craig (philosopher)|Edward Craig]], ''Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy'', ed. Taylor & Francis, 1998, {{ISBN|978-0-415-07310-3}}, p. 20</ref> He also wrote poetry, fiction, and non-fiction books on economics, politics, and literature. Lahbabi was one of the founders of the Union of Arab Writers of the Maghreb and the review Afaq (Horizons). He was nominated for the 1987 [[Nobel Prize]] for Literature.
