{{DISPLAYTITLE:Textual tradition of ''The Tale of Genji''}}
''[[The Tale of Genji]]'' is one of the best-known works of [[classical Japanese literature]], and the number of manuscript copies of it is very large. It was originally written by [[Murasaki Shikibu]], a lady-in-waiting at the [[Heian period|Heian]] court, at the beginning of the eleventh century, but the earliest extant manuscript was copied by [[Fujiwara no Teika]] roughly two centuries later.

== Overview ==
''[[The Tale of Genji]]'' was copied extensively in the pre-modern era.{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} The scholar {{illm|Kikan Ikeda|ja|池田亀鑑}} once performed an extensive study of 300 manuscript copies of the work,{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} and even counting only manuscripts copied before the end of the [[Muromachi period]] in the mid-16th century the number comes to roughly 100.{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}

The earliest of these surviving copies, dating from the early [[Kamakura period]],{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} are the ''{{illm|Aobyōshi-bon|ja|青表紙本}}'' produced by [[Fujiwara no Teika]]{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} and the ''{{illm|Kawachi-bon|ja|河内本}}'' produced by [[Minamoto no Mitsuyuki]] and his son [[Minamoto no Chikayuki|Chikayuki]] <small>([[:ja:源親行|ja]])</small>.{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}

== Early copying ==
[[Murasaki Shikibu Nikki|Murasaki's diary]] records that by the winter of 1008 ''Genji'' was already in circulation,{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} and so must have already begun to be copied and distributed at this time.{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} Because of the circumstances of copying of ''[[monogatari]]'' literature, which were treated as light entertainments for court ladies,{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} numerous errors crept into these early copies,{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} and as those copies were copied the errors multiplied exponentially.{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} Entire chapters began to be added to the work, coming to around 60 chapters rather than the 54 that became the standard.{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}

=== Kamakura editors ===
Fujiwara no Teika, according to his diary the ''[[Meigetsuki]]'', was robbed on the [[Japanese calendar|16th day of the second month]] of 1225,{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} and his copy of ''Genji'' was one of the items that were stolen.{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} Teika had apparently been working on editing a "true version" of ''Genji'' (possibly the surviving ''Aobyōshi-bon'') since the eleventh month of the previous year,{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} but in his diary he bemoaned the many variations between the various manuscripts in circulation.{{efn|尋求所々、雖見合諸本、猶狼藉未散不審}}{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}

Chikayuki, who began his editing of the ''Kawachi-bon'' in 1236,{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} similarly wrote of the variations between the manuscripts he had available to him.{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}

=== Lost manuscripts ===
The texts that were available to the early Kamakura editors may have included:
*the ''Nijō no Sochi Korefusa-bon'' (二条帥伊房本);{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}
*the ''Reizei no Chūnagon Tomotaka-bon'' (冷泉中納言朝隆本);{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}
*the ''Horikawa no Sadaijin Toshifusa-bon'' (堀川左大臣俊房本);{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}
*the ''{{illm|Ju-Ichi-i Reishi-hon|ja|従一位麗子本源氏物語}}'';{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}
*the ''Hosshōji Kanpaku-bon'' (法性寺関白本);{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}
*the ''Gojō no Sanmi Shunzei-bon'' (五条三位俊成本);{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}
*the ''Kyōgoku no Chūnagon Teika-bon'' (京極中納言定家本);{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}
and at least thirteen other manuscripts whose names are known,{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}} as well one copy that was supposedly produced by [[Fujiwara no Yukinari]].{{sfnm|1a1=Akiyama|1a2=Abe|1a3=Shinohara|1y=1983|1p=433}}
